# Machine specific settings for the stats pipeline.
#
# deploy.sh copies this to /etc/hails-stats/config.env the first time and never touches it again,
# so your edits are safe across redeploys. Every systemd unit reads it, so after changing anything
# here run:  systemctl restart hails-perf && systemctl start hails-stats.service
#
# Everything has a working default. You can leave the whole file alone and the dashboard still
# comes up, you just will not get service uptime or a public network map.

# ---- Performance page: what to chart ------------------------------------------------------------

# Hardware is discovered when the collector starts, so you normally set none of this. Every disk,
# filesystem and physical interface found gets its own card on the page, and each keeps its own
# history, so adding hardware later does not disturb what is already recorded.
#
# These two only exist to pin the list by hand if discovery ever picks wrong. Comma separated.
#HAILS_PERF_DISK=vda,vdb
#HAILS_PERF_NIC=eth0

# How often to sample /proc, in seconds. 10 gives you a genuinely useful 1 minute average. Raising
# it saves a trivial amount of CPU and costs you resolution.
#HAILS_PERF_INTERVAL=10

# ---- Performance page: what to watch ------------------------------------------------------------

# Local systemd units to report, comma separated. The .service suffix is added if you leave it off.
# These give you exact restart times and per service memory for free.
HAILS_PERF_UNITS=caddy.service,docker.service

# Sites to probe over the network, so you get real availability and latency rather than just
# "the process is running". Format is name|url|healthy status codes, separated by semicolons.
#
# The status codes matter more than they look. Plenty of healthy sites answer a redirect or an auth
# challenge on their root, and if you only accept 200 they will show as down forever. Check what
# yours actually returns first:  curl -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\n' https://your.site/
#
# Empty by default, so a fresh install never fires requests at hosts it was not told about.
#HAILS_PERF_TARGETS=site|https://example.com/|200 ; shortener|https://l.example.com/|200,301 ; dashboard|https://stats.example.com/|401

# How often to probe those sites, in seconds. 300 is a good balance. Going much lower means real
# traffic to your own sites all day, and it is the first thing to raise if the collector ever costs
# more CPU than you would like.
#HAILS_PERF_HTTP=300

# How often to read systemd and docker state, in seconds. These barely change, so 300 is plenty.
# Note this is why a container you just restarted can take up to 5 minutes to update on the page.
#HAILS_PERF_LOCAL=300

# ---- Network map --------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Name shown on the map and in its page titles.
HAILS_MAP_ORG=example

# Friendly labels for the localhost ports your Caddyfile proxies to, so the map reads as
# "link shortener" instead of "127.0.0.1:3000". Format is port|label, comma separated.
#HAILS_MAP_PORTSVC=4001|Link shortener,4002|Radio,4003|Links page

# The map always writes a private copy to /srv/stats/map.html behind your dashboard login.
#
# Set this to ALSO publish a sanitised public version into that host's static root, as
# network.html. The public version drops ports, localhost upstreams, filesystem paths and any host
# behind auth. Leave it unset and no public page is produced at all, which is the safe default.
#HAILS_MAP_PUBLIC_HOST=example.com
#HAILS_MAP_CANON=https://example.com/network.html

# ---- Aggregate view --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Hosts kept out of the "All domains" view only, comma separated, matched as a prefix of the
# hostname. Each still gets its own per domain scope and stays in the Domain dropdown, so it can be
# inspected deliberately.
#
# Useful for a host whose traffic is mostly noise. A url shortener, for example, tends to be hammered
# by vulnerability scanners, and that skews every aggregate panel and KPI.
#HAILS_AGG_EXCLUDE=short.

# Hosts removed from the pipeline ENTIRELY, comma separated, matched as a prefix of the hostname.
# Stronger than HAILS_AGG_EXCLUDE above: no split log, no scope, no pages, and nothing in the
# warehouse either. A Referer pointing at one is stripped too, so it cannot reappear elsewhere.
#HAILS_DROP_HOSTS=short.

# ---- Scanner probes -------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Scanner requests stay in every count, because they were served and they did cost you bandwidth.
# What they lose is their identity: the url becomes the sentinel /(probe) and the Referer is deleted.
# That collapses hundreds of junk urls into one row and stops a forged Referer from inventing a
# referrer that never linked to you.
#
# Unset uses the built in token list. Set it to "none" to turn masking off, since an empty value has
# to keep meaning the default. Tokens match a path segment, never a substring. A trailing slash means
# a directory; without one it matches that filename and its dotted variants, so ".env" also catches
# .env.local while leaving .envrc alone.
#
# Try any change as a dry run first. It prints what would be masked and writes nothing:
#
#   zcat -f /var/log/caddy/access.log* | hails-stats-pre.py --probe-report
#
# A token showing a 2xx against a real endpoint of yours is a false positive, and this is not
# reversible: the url and the referrer go from the log path and the warehouse at the same moment.
#HAILS_PROBE_PATHS=

# ---- Referrers ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Your own registrable domains, comma separated. A referrer whose host is one of these, or any
# subdomain of one, lands on the Internal pages and everything else lands on the external ones.
# Worth setting if you run more than one site, otherwise your own cross links bury the outside
# traffic. Unset means every referrer is external, and the Internal pages generate empty rather than
# disappearing.
#HAILS_INTERNAL_DOMAINS=example.com,example.net

# ---- Events warehouse -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# How many days of raw events to keep. The rollups behind the long windows are never pruned, so this
# only bounds the raw table and the interned url, address, agent and referrer rows, which is where
# the growth actually is on a public server. Anything under 62 days is raised to 62: the reports read
# a 30 day window plus the 30 before it, so a shorter retention would silently empty a page.
#HAILS_EVENT_DAYS=90

# How stale the warehouse may be, in seconds, before the pages fall back to reading the log.
# A stalled ingest does not look like an error otherwise: the pages render complete, well formed and
# entirely zero. Measured against the newest event in the whole table, not per host, since a quiet
# site can go hours without traffic.
#HAILS_DB_STALE_S=1800

# ---- Fonts --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Roboto is bundled with the project, so no page calls Google. This is the URL the stylesheets point
# at. Leave it unset and it is /fonts, served from /srv/stats/fonts alongside the dashboard, which is
# what deploy.sh sets up by default.
#
# Serving from another host means the browser treats the font as cross origin, so that host MUST
# send Access-Control-Allow-Origin or the font is blocked and the page quietly falls back to the
# system stack. Set FONT_DIR in .env to match wherever you point this.
#HAILS_FONT_BASE=https://assets.example.com/fonts

# ---- Requests served counter --------------------------------------------------------------------

# hails-served.py totals every request in the bandwidth rollup and writes served.js into this
# directory, holding the sentence "Over N requests served". A public page can load that file and
# show the figure. Refreshed once per regen by hails-stats.sh, so every 15 minutes.
#
# Point it at a directory your web server already serves. If you run several sites, use a shared
# asset host so they all read the same file and stay in step.
#
# Leave it unset and nothing is written at all, which is the safe default.
#HAILS_SERVED_ROOT=/srv/assets.example.com

# Head start added to the live count, for traffic served before the rollup existed. Zero by default,
# so the figure on the page is the real one.
#HAILS_SERVED_BASELINE=0

# ---- Storage --------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Where the durable history lives: the events warehouse, the bandwidth rollup and the performance
# rings. This sits outside /srv/stats on purpose, because that directory is wiped and rebuilt on
# every regen.
#HAILS_PERF_DIR=/var/lib/hails-stats
#HAILS_ROLLUP=/var/lib/hails-stats/bandwidth.json
